\begin{center}
Abstract

\end{center}
The defining challenge for the African continent in the early 21st century rests on the ability of the African Union through its regional economic communities and member states to confront a growing number of complex, transnational threats which risk eroding the steady progress made on peace and security efforts during the past two decades. In this work, I assess the state rationales that inform peacekeeping contributions. I evaluate the dominant theories within the peacekeeping literature while offering something new. I aim to model the underlying data generating process that determines which African states are most likely to contribute peacekeepers and assess the marginal effects of regional integration. To accomplish this, I derive a statistical model using maximum likelihood and utilize Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) simulation to calculate the probability that an African state will support peacekeeping operations. I then assess the results through a disciplined case selection of current United Nations peacekeeping operations within the Democratic Republic of Congo, the Central African Republic, and Mali. The thrust of the argument centers on an assumption that regional integration and regional security are mutually reinforcing. Where I find stronger regional ties, I expect to find ``African solutions to African problems.''

