# Introduction

## Research problem
On July 11th, 2000 fifty-three African states signed the Constitutive Act of the African Union during the Thirty-Sixth Ordinary Session of the Assembly of Heads of State and Government in Lom√©, Togo. The establishment of the African Union (AU) provided both the legal and institutional framework required to address the growing number of complex challenges on the continent. The adoption of the Constitutive Act represented a fundamental shift in African-led peace and security efforts. Under the auspices of the former Organization of African Unity (OAU), traditional principles of national sovereignty and noninterference were upheld often at the expense of inaction and perceived indifference. For the first time, African states agreed to "the right of the Union to intervene in a member state pursuant to a decision of the Assembly in respect of grave circumstances including war crimes, genocide, and crimes against humanity'' (African Union, 2000, p. 7). The transition from a policy of non-interference to non-indifference represented a fundamental shift for peace and security efforts on the continent.  

During the 20th century, the preponderance of peace operations centered on localized instability within Africa. Since the early aughts, however, conflicts have often metastasized into regional instability - most recently across the Sahel region, Lake Chad Basin, and the Horn of Africa. The complex interaction of socio-economic challenges, rising violent extremism, and the intertwining of organized crime and political corruption defines a new source of instability that requires coordinated, multidimensional responses from the international community (Karlsrud, 2017). The ability of the African Union and its regional institutions to contain current instability in Mali, the Democratic Republic of Congo, and the Central African Republic (CAR) warrants reassessment of complex UN mandates vetted against limited organic capabilities required for sustained operations. There exists a delta between strategic objectives and tactical boots-on-ground realities. It requires troop and police-contributing countries to leverage their comparative advantages while seeking strategic assets from western partners and allies. And it requires targeted international assistance to improve training, equipping, and modernizing African military units for UN deployment. The APSA argues that holistic solutions that bring together political, socio-economic, and military capabilities must be tied to policy harmonization at the UN, AU, and REC levels. Burden-sharing -- vice institutional competition -- must be the guiding principle. 
